<h2 id="project-management">Project Management</h2>

<p>The organization of this project spec is by feature type. However, it is encouraged that you work through a little of each feature type rather than trying to complete an entire feature type before moving to the next. We encourage you to use an Agile approach as much as possible to complete this assignment, and to review the work and develop estimated milestones before you begin. <strong>Any good set of milestones will allow for some slippage before the project is due.</strong></p>

<p>We <em>highly</em> encourage you to have attempted some of the business intelligence queries before the Advanced ActiveRecord class.</p>

<h2 id="postman">Postman</h2>

<p>We have adapted this project from previous cohorts and have rewritten a fully functional test suite right within Postman. By importing the JSON file noted below, you can open the Postman â€œRunnerâ€ and execute a large suite of tests.</p>

<p>Note: in order to pass the project, not ALL of the Postman tests will be passing. You will need to examine the tests you NEED to run, since weâ€™re giving students some choice in how to build the application.</p>

<h4 id="importing-the-test-suite">Importing the Test Suite</h4>

<p>Download the test suite <a href="./RailsEngine.postman_collection.json">from this URL</a>. In Postman, in the top left corner, click on the â€œImportâ€ button, and drag the downloaded JSON file over the interface or use the file selector to locate the file on your operating system.</p>

<p>Next, youâ€™ll â€œconfirmâ€ the import. The test suite should display as a â€œPostman Collection v2.1â€ and import as a â€œCollectionâ€. Click the â€œImportâ€ button to continue.</p>

<p>On the left side of your Postman interface, you should see a â€œRails Engineâ€ entry with â€œ19 requestsâ€.</p>

<h4 id="running-the-tests">Running the Tests</h4>

<p>There are two ways to run the test suite: one endpoint at a time, or the whole suite.</p>

<h4 id="running-one-endpoint-at-a-time">Running one endpoint at a time</h4>

<p>As you develop your endpoints, run â€œrails sâ€ and find the appropriate endpoint within the Postman collection you imported. For example, â€œGet All Merchantsâ€. When you select â€œGet All Merchantsâ€ from the list, you should see a Postman tab open, pre-populated with everything you need to connect to the endpoint in your code and see if it works correctly.</p>

<p>Click the â€œSendâ€ button in the top right corner.</p>

<p>In the lower portion of the Postman interface, you should see â€œBodyâ€, â€œCookiesâ€, â€œHeadersâ€ and a spot that says something like â€œTest Results (7/7)â€. This would indicate that 7 tests passed out of 7. If you see, for example, 3/7 then 7 tests passed and 4 did not.</p>

<p>You can click on the â€œTest Results (7/7)â€ to see which tests passed.</p>

<p>The error messages arenâ€™t that great, but weâ€™re here to help you diagnose the problems.</p>

<p><strong>IMPORTANT</strong> some of the endpoints include EDGE CASE testing, which should be saved as â€œextensionâ€ work.</p>

<h4 id="running-the-full-test-suite">Running the full test suite</h4>

<p>In the top left corner of the Postman interface, youâ€™ll see a â€œRunnerâ€ button. Click that and a new Postman window will appear. From here, you can select â€œRails Engineâ€ from the list of â€œAll Collectionsâ€.</p>

<p>Next you can select/deselect which tests youâ€™d like to run. Next, click the â€œRun Rails Engineâ€ button.</p>

<p>As it runs, it will show you which tests are passing or failing.</p>

